<a name="0">[0]</a> <a href="#0" id=0>But in the scaling-out model, experiments that deploy an array of small instruments can exploit the coming explosion in cheaper commodity technology.</a>
<a name="1">[1]</a> <a href="#1" id=1>Some scientists are building billion-dollar facilities, such as astronomy's Large Synoptic Survey Telescope or the Large Hadron Collider, which are only affordable as international collaborations.</a>
<a name="2">[2]</a> <a href="#2" id=2>And once these peta-scale experiments are switched on they will produce roughly the same amount of data each year -- merely linear growth.</a>
<a name="3">[3]</a> <a href="#3" id=3>Exponential growth occurs when a new generation of instruments leapfrogs the previous generation, which become obsolete.</a>
